{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14086"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583912"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14086"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14086"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.09,0.07,0.08,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52695"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6754"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14086"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1528"},{"type":"tags","id":"1783"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52695"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of pain and swelling in her fingers and toes. She works as a typist and finds it increasingly difficult to perform her job. She has an eight-year history of psoriasis affecting her elbows, knees, and scalp. She takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is swelling and tenderness of several distal interphalangeal joints of her hands (Image) and feet. Her right second toe appears swollen along its entire length. Scaly, erythematous plaques are visible on her elbows and knees.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to show changes specific to her condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-CCP antibodies","Serum uric acid","Rheumatoid factor","C-reactive protein","Plain radiographs of hands and feet"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of psoriatic arthritis, given her history of psoriasis, nail changes, and the pattern of joint involvement, including distal interphalangeal joint inflammation and dactylitis (sausage digit). Psoriatic arthritis typically shows symptoms ten years after the skin changes are first noted though it can also occur before as well. In investigating this condition, \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain radiographs of hands and feet\u003C/strong\u003E are most likely to show changes specific to psoriatic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlain radiographs can reveal characteristic features of psoriatic arthritis, including pencil-in-cup deformities, periostitis, joint space narrowing, erosions, and new bone formation. These changes, particularly when seen in the distal interphalangeal joints, are highly suggestive of psoriatic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid factor\u003C/strong\u003E is typically negative in psoriatic arthritis. A positive rheumatoid factor is more commonly associated with rheumatoid arthritis. The absence of rheumatoid factor in a patient with inflammatory arthritis and psoriasis supports the diagnosis of psoriatic arthritis but is not specific to the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-CCP antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E (anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide) are also usually negative in psoriatic arthritis. Like rheumatoid factor, these antibodies are more commonly positive in rheumatoid arthritis. Their absence can help differentiate psoriatic arthritis from rheumatoid arthritis but does not provide specific diagnostic information for psoriatic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E (CRP) is a non-specific marker of inflammation. While it may be elevated in psoriatic arthritis, indicating active inflammation, it is not specific to the condition and can be elevated in many inflammatory conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum uric acid\u003C/strong\u003E levels are typically normal in psoriatic arthritis. Elevated uric acid is associated with gout, which can sometimes be confused with psoriatic arthritis due to similar joint involvement patterns. However, normal uric acid levels neither confirm nor exclude psoriatic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to plain radiographs, other investigations that may be useful in diagnosing and assessing psoriatic arthritis include magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for early detection of joint changes, and ultrasonography for assessing synovitis and enthesitis. However, plain radiographs remain a crucial initial investigation due to their ability to show characteristic changes of psoriatic arthritis.  Management focuses on analgesia and lifestyle changes, however oral corticosteroids and disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs also have a role in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Psoriatic arthritis often involves the distal interphalangeal joints and can present with dactylitis (\u0027sausage digits\u0027).","Plain radiographs of hands and feet are important initial investigations in suspected psoriatic arthritis, showing characteristic features such as pencil-in-cup deformities and periostitis."],"references":["Stanway A, Fox-Lewish S, McManus E, White D.  Psoriatic arthritis. In: Dermnet NZ [online]. 2005.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/psoriatic-arthritis","Raychaudhuri S, Helliwell P, Espinoza L, Taylor W. Psoriatic arthrtitis. In: Best Medical Journal Best Practice [online]. 2023. Available at: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/524","Daniel B. The multiple comorbidities of psoriasis: The importance of a holistic approach. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2020;49:433-7. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/july/the-multiple-comorbidities-of-psoriasis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14086"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20977"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20977"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BBWnqfJU5a7Uo7B3snFQ5qgSDdIPsB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BBWnqfJU5a7Uo7B3snFQ5qgSDdIPsB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38053"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T11:49:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T12:11:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6754"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52695"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":fal